===Life cycle===
''Tarebia granifera'' is both <!-- [[Parthenogenesis|parthenogenetic]] -->[[单性生殖|单性生殖]] and <!-- [[ovoviviparous|ovoviviparous]] -->[[卵胎生|卵胎生]],<ref name="Appleton 2009"/> although males have been reported.<ref name="nis"/> These are characteristics which are undoubtedly key to its success as an invader.<ref name="Appleton 2009"/> For example, no males have been found amongst hundreds dissected from KwaZulu-Natal, it is probable that a few are present.<ref name="Appleton 2009"/> Males were found in most (6/7) populations examined in <!-- [[Puerto_Rico|Puerto Rico]] -->[[波多黎各|波多黎各]] but were generally uncommon at up to 22.7% of the population (mean 4.6%).<ref name="Appleton 2009"/><ref>Chaniotis B. N., Butler J. M., Ferguson F. F. & Jobin W. R. (1980). "Presence of males in Puerto Rican ''Thiara'' (''Tarebia'') ''granifera'' (Gastropoda: Thiaridae), a snail thought to be parthenogenetic". ''{{tsl|en|Caribbean Journal of Science||Caribbean Journal of Science}}'' '''16''': 95–97. [http://academic.uprm.edu/publications/cjs/VOL16/P095-098.PDF PDF] {{Wayback|url=http://academic.uprm.edu/publications/cjs/VOL16/P095-098.PDF |date=20111001053515 }}.</ref> Live sperm were present in the testes of these males but the {{tsl|en|reproductive system of gastropods||genitalia}} were apparently non-functional.<ref name="Appleton 2009"/> R. Tucker Abbott (1952)<ref name="Abbott 1952"/> failed to find sperm in the gonads of male ''Tarebia granifera'' from Florida.<ref name="Appleton 2009"/> Most ''Tarebia granifera'' are therefore <!-- [[Cloning|clones]] -->[[克隆|克隆]] of the female parent.<ref name="Appleton 2009"/>

<!-- [[Embryo|Embryo]] -->[[胚胎|胚胎]]s develop in a <!-- 页面不存在 -->[[brood_pouch_(gastropod)|brood pouch]].<ref name="Appleton 2009"/> This pouch is a compartmentalized structure lying immediately above the {{tsl|en|Digestive system of gastropods||oesophagus}} and develops only after the snail has reached maturity.<ref name="Appleton 2009"/> Its size expands as the number of embryos increases.<ref name="Appleton 2009"/><ref name="Abbott 1952"/><ref name="Malek 1962"/> ''Tarebia granifera'' has 1–77 embryos in its brood pouch.<ref name="Appleton 2009"/>

Tucker Abbott (1952),<ref name="Abbott 1952"/> Chaniotis et al. (1980)<ref name="Chaniotis 1980"/> and WHO (1981)<ref name="WHO 1981">W.H.O. (1981). "Data sheet on the biological control agent ''Thiara granifera'' (Lamarck)". <!-- [[World_Health_Organization|World Health Organization]] -->[[世界卫生组织|世界卫生组织]], Geneva, VBC/BCDS/81.17.</ref> cite the same<!--frightening--> statistic that females can give birth to one juvenile every 12 hours.<ref name="Appleton 2009"/> Young snails emerge through a birth pore on the right side of the head.<ref name="Appleton 2009"/> The newborn shell is <1–2 mm in height with between 1.5 and 4.8 whorls.<ref name="Appleton 2009"/> The size of juveniles at birth is 0.7–2.1 mm.<ref name="Appleton 2009"/> According to Chen (2003)<ref name="Chen 2003"/> these newborns have a high survival rate in the field.<ref name="Appleton 2009"/>

Attainment of <!-- [[sexual_maturity|sexual maturity]] -->[[性成熟|性成熟]] in ''Tarebia granifera'' is generally indicated by the size of the smallest snail observed to give birth rather than a histological assessment of the development of the gonad and associated reproductive structures.<ref name="Appleton 2009"/> Appleton & Nadasan (2002)<ref name="Appleton Nadasan 2002"/> estimated onset of maturity at 10–12 mm shell height but unpublished data<ref name="Appleton 2009"/> suggest a height closer to 8 mm in line with other published studies.<ref name="Appleton 2009"/> Tucker Abbott (1952)<ref name="Abbott 1952"/> estimated sexual maturity at between 5.5 and 8.0 mm at different stations over a short stretch of river in Florida.<ref name="Appleton 2009"/> Chaniotis et al. (1980)<ref name="Chaniotis 1980"/> gave a similar estimate of 6.0–7.0 mm from a cohort of laboratory-bred snails in Puerto Rico.<ref name="Appleton 2009"/>

Appleton et al. (2009)<ref name="Appleton 2009"/> extrapolated data by Yong et al. (1987),<ref name="Yong 1987">Yong M., Sanchez R., Perera G., Ferrer R. & Amador O. (1987). "Seasonal studies of two populations of ''Tarebia granifera''". ''<!-- 页面不存在 -->[[Walkerana|Walkerana]]'' '''2''': 159–163.</ref> Ferrer López et al. (1989)<ref name="Ferrer López 1989">{{in lang|es}} Ferrer López J. R., Perera de Puga G. & Yong Cong M. (1989). "Estudio de la morfometría de los 4 poblaciones de ''Tarebia granifera'' en condiciones de laboratorio". ''{{tsl|en|Revista Cubana de Medicina Tropical||Revista Cubana de Medicina Tropical}}'' '''43''': 26–30.</ref> and by Fernández et al.(1992)<ref name="Fernández 1992">{{in lang|es}} Fernández L. D., Casalis A. E., Masa A. M. & Perez M. V. (1992). "Estudio preliminar de la variación de ''Tarebia granifera'' (Lamarck), Río Hatibonico, Camagüey". ''{{tsl|en|Revista Cubana de Medicina Tropical||Revista Cubana de Medicina Tropical}}'' '''44''': 66–70.</ref> and they resulted that sexual maturity is reached at an age of about five months.<ref name="Appleton 2009"/> Reported variation in maturation period varies from 97–143 days (3.2–4.8 months)<ref name="Chaniotis 1980"/> under the laboratory conditions to 6–12 months, also from laboratory data.<ref name="Appleton 2009"/><ref name="Abbott 1952"/><ref name="WHO 1981"/> It is difficult to relate shell size at the onset of maturity to age since the size structure of populations vary over time and from one locality to another.<ref name="Appleton 2009"/>

Dissection of ''Tarebia granifera'' showed <!-- [[blastula|blastula]] -->[[囊胚|囊胚]] stage embryos in the brood pouches of snails as small as 8 mm shell height.<ref name="Appleton 2009"/> Small numbers of shelled embryos, including {{tsl|en|veliger||veliger}}s, were found in snails of 10–14 mm but became more plentiful in snails >14 mm and especially those >20 mm.<ref name="Appleton 2009"/> Importantly, unshelled embryos (blastula, <!-- [[gastrula|gastrula]] -->[[原腸胚形成|原腸胚形成]] and <!-- [[trochophore|trochophore]] -->[[担轮幼虫|担轮幼虫]] stages) were not found in snails >16 mm and the numbers of shelled embryos themselves decreased in the largest snails, >24 mm.<ref name="Appleton 2009"/> This suggests that differentiation of <!-- [[germ_cell|germinal cells]] -->[[生殖细胞|生殖细胞]] in the ovary and their subsequent arrival in the brood pouch as blastulae is not a continuous process over a breeding season but occurs as one or more 'cohorts' or 'pulses' which stop before the birth rate of young snails reaches its maximum.<ref name="Appleton 2009"/> So it seems that while the first birth may occur in snails as small as 8 mm, these are few and most juveniles are born to snails >14 mm.<ref name="Appleton 2009"/> The size of the shell of the parent at peak release of juveniles is 24.0 mm.<ref name="Appleton 2009"/>

The {{tsl|en|reproductive biology||reproductive biology}} of ''Tarebia granifera'' needs to be investigated in detail before its {{tsl|en|population dynamics||population dynamics}} can be properly interpreted from quantitative sampling.<ref name="Appleton 2009"/>

===寄生蟲===
本物種在東南亞為多個[[吸蟲綱|吸蟲綱]]物種的[[中間宿主|中間宿主]]<ref name="Appleton 2009"/>，當中有多個物種屬於[[Heterophyidae|Heterophyidae]]科，而且有報告指部分物種對人類可進行[[机会性感染|机会性感染]]<ref name="Appleton 2009"/><ref name="Watson 1960">{{cite journal |last1=Watson |first=J. M. |year=1960 |journal=''[[Medical_Helminthology|Medical Helminthology]]'' |volume=? |pages=1–487 |publisher=Baillière Tindall & Cox |location=[[倫敦|London]]（[[UK|UK]]） |language=en }}</ref> and another, ''{{tsl|en|Centrocestus formosanus||Centrocestus formosanus}}'' (Nishigori, 1924), is an important gill parasite of fish.<ref name="Appleton 2009"/> ''Tarebia granifera'' also serves as intermediate host for the philopthalmid eyefluke ''<!-- 页面不存在 -->[[Philopthalmus_gralli|Philopthalmus gralli]]'' Mathis & Ledger, 1910 which has recently (2005) been reported affecting <!-- [[ostrich|ostrich]] -->[[鸵鸟科|鸵鸟科]]es ''<!-- [[Struthio_camelus|Struthio camelus]] -->[[鸵鸟|鸵鸟]]'' on farms in Zimbabwe.<ref name="Appleton 2009"/><ref>Mukaratirwa S., Hove T., Cindzi Z. M., Maononga D. B., Taruvinga M. & Matenga E. (2005). "First report of an outbreak of the oriental eyefluke ''Philopthalmus gralli'' (Mathis & Ledger, 1910), in commercially reared ostriches (''Struthio camelus'') in Zimbabwe". ''<!-- 页面不存在 -->[[Onderstepoort_Journal_of_Veterinary_Research|Onderstepoort Journal of Veterinary Research]]'' '''72''': 203–206.</ref> The snail host implicated in this outbreak was ''Melanoides tuberculata'' but the rapid spread and high population densities achieved by ''Tarebia granifera'', which appears to be replacing ''Melanoides tuberculata'' in South Africa, may exacerbate the problem in the future.<ref name="Appleton 2009"/>

For many years ''Tarebia granifera'' was believed to be an intermediate host for the Asian lungfluke ''<!-- [[Paragonimus_westermani|Paragonimus westermani]] -->[[衛氏肺吸蟲|衛氏肺吸蟲]]'' (Kerbert, 1878), but Michelson showed in 1992 that this was erroneous.<ref name="Appleton 2009"/><ref>Michelson E. (1992). "''Thiara granifera'': a victim of authoritarianism?" ''<!-- 页面不存在 -->[[Malacological_Review|Malacological Review]]'' '''25''': 67–71.</ref>

===Other interspecific relationships===
''Tarebia granifera'' have been associated with the disappearance of two{{Which|date=August 2010}} indigenous benthic gastropod species from rivers in <!-- [[Puerto_Rico|Puerto Rico]] -->[[波多黎各|波多黎各]] and have displaced the vegetation-associated pulmonate ''{{tsl|en|Biomphalaria glabrata||Biomphalaria glabrata}}'' from streams and ponds on several Caribbean islands.<ref name="Appleton 2009"/><ref name="Prentice 1983"/><ref name="Samadi 1997">Samadi S., Balzan C., Delay B. & Pointier J.-P. (1997). "Local distribution and abundance of thiarid snails in recently colonized rivers from the Caribbean area". ''Malacological Review'' '''30''': 45–52.</ref> Although the responsible mechanism is not understood, this has led to suggestions that it could be useful as a <!-- [[biocontrol|biocontrol]] -->[[生物防治|生物防治]] agent in snail control operations within integrated <!-- [[schistosomiasis|schistosomiasis]] -->[[血吸虫病|血吸虫病]] control programmes.<ref name="Appleton 2009"/> They probably also <!-- [[Competition_(biology)|compete]] -->[[竞争_(生物学)|竞争 (生物学)]] for space and resources (e.g. food) with indigenous infaunal and epifaunal invertebrates, especially where its densities are high.<ref name="Appleton 2009"/> Under such conditions it is likely to alter the structure and <!-- [[biodiversity|biodiversity]] -->[[生物多樣性|生物多樣性]] of the entire benthic communities of invaded habitats and perhaps the vegetation-associated communities as well.<ref name="Appleton 2009"/>

Anecdotal reports and observations suggest that in <!-- [[KwaZulu-Natal|KwaZulu-Natal]] -->[[夸祖魯-納塔爾省|夸祖魯-納塔爾省]] the indigenous thiarid ''<!-- [[Melanoides_tuberculata|Melanoides tuberculata]] -->[[瘤拟黑螺|瘤拟黑螺]]'' is becoming less common and pressure from the spread of ''Tarebia granifera'', particularly at high densities, is a possible explanation.<ref name="Appleton 2009"/> Like ''Tarebia granifera'', ''Melanoides tuberculata'' is parthenogenetic and ovoviviparous, grows to a similar size, are similar in size at first birth and juvenile output.<ref name="Appleton 2009"/> Data from several habitats where the species occur {{tsl|en|sympatrically||sympatrically}} show however that in all such situations ''Tarebia granifera'' becomes numerically dominant.<ref name="Appleton 2009"/>

''Tarebia granifera'' is likely to impact on another South-African indigenous thiarid, the poorly known ''<!-- 页面不存在 -->[[Thiara_amarula|Thiara amarula]]'' in the saline St. Lucia estuary system.<ref name="Appleton 2009"/>

Studies on the ecological impact of ''Tarebia granifera'' are urgently needed.<ref name="Appleton 2009"/>

==Human importance==
In addition to its role as intermediate host for several economically important trematode species, ''Tarebia granifera'' has colonized <!-- [[water_reservoir|water reservoir]] -->[[水庫|水庫]]s, dams and ponds on the premises of three large industrial plants in northern KwaZulu-Natal and been pumped out of at least one of them, blocking <!-- [[water_pipe|water pipe]] -->[[管路系統|管路系統]]s and damaging equipment.<ref name="Appleton 2009"/> This generally happens when snail densities are high and the damage is due to individuals being crushed so that pieces of shell and soft tissue are carried into machinery.<ref name="Appleton 2009"/> Details of the nature and extent of this damage and the costs incurred are not available.<ref name="Appleton 2009"/> There is no doubt that ''Tarebia granifera'' is able to pass unharmed through <!-- [[pumps|pumps]] -->[[泵|泵]], probably as juveniles.<ref name="Appleton 2009"/>

